body.p:
Thanks to the growing accessibility of tools for building and deploying interactive databases and applications, coupled with the abundance of available digital material, community-driven archiving has seen significant growth. Activists and historians are creating digital archives focused on specific causes or geographical regions. For instance, bak.ma (
                ) serves as an impressive archive of videos documenting human rights struggles in Turkiye, built by Turkish historians and digital creators. Similarly, the Urban Video Archive (
                ) documents the struggles of disenfranchised Brazilians, highlighting state brutality and their fight for rights. This archive is co-created by a video activist collective from Rio de Janeiro, an urban sociologist, and a media scholar and technologist. Yet, these initiatives rarely achieve the visibility enjoyed by large, well-funded institutions.
